93</p></td><td><p>99</p></td><td><p>94</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>8,147</p></td><td><p>10,382</p></td><td><p>11,353</p></td><td><p>11,692</p></td><td><p>11,997</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /> <br /><p>Across the UK, more individuals are being tested for hepatitis C and over the last 5 years particular improvements have been seen in primary care where surveillance indicates that testing has risen by 21% in England (vi).</p><br /><p>Citations</p><p>(i) Health Protection Report Vol 5. No. 29 22 July 2011</p><p>(ii) Health Protection Report Vol 6. No. 30 27 July 2012</p><p>(iii) Health Protection Report Vol.7 No. 30 26 July 2013</p><p>(iv) Health Protection Report Vol 98 No. 29 25 July 2014</p><p>(v) Health Protection Report Vol 9 No. 26 24 July 2015</p><p>(vi) Hepatitis C in the UK; 2015 report. Public Health England</p><br /> <br /> <br />","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-11-11T16:41:51.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425726/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425726/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-03","Hepatitis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people in each age group were diagnosed with hepatitis C in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","14651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425727","Department of Health","false","2015-11-10","<p>The attached table gives a count of finished consultant episodes with a primary diagnosis of diabetes and a primary or secondary procedure of amputation 2009-10 to 2013-14.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-11-10T17:46:23.74Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425727/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425727/answer","FCEs- Diabetes and amputations 2009-14.xlsx","FCEs- Diabetes and amputations 2009-14.xlsx","FCEs- Diabetes and amputations 2009-14","FCEs- Diabetes and amputations 2009-14","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425727/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-03","Diabetes: Orthopaedics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many amputations were performed on people with diabetes in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","14652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425728","Department of Health","false","2015-11-11","<p>The number of positive rotavirus laboratory reports each year since 2013 is shown in the table below. These data indicate that there has been a decrease of approximately 10,000 annual cases of rotavirus since the introduction of rotavirus immunisation in July 2013.</p><br /><p>Table 1: The number of positive rotavirus laboratory reports recorded annually since 2013.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of positive rotavirus laboratory reports</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>14,950</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>4,447</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>5,035*</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /> <br /><p><em></em></p><p><em>Source:</em> PHE Second Generation Surveillance System (SGSS) laboratory reporting database</p><p><em>Note:</em> *Figure to end October 2015.</p><br /><p>Deaths from rotavirus in the United Kingdom are rare. However precise numbers of deaths are difficult to quantify accurately as mortality is usually low and reported simply as death due to gastrointestinal disease. It was previously estimated that there may have been up to three to four rotavirus associated deaths a year in England and Wales (Jit et al., 2007). Following a recommendation from the Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation (JCVI), the independent expert committee that advises the Government on immunisation, the rotavirus vaccine was introduced in July 2013. Since then, there have been no reported rotavirus-related deaths in the eligible cohort.</p><br /><p>Immunisation against rotavirus is offered as a two dose schedule to infants at two and three months of age. The table below indicates the number of rotavirus vaccinations given by year.</p><br /><p>Table 2: Number of general practitioner (GP) registered patients who received (a) a 1st dose and (b) a 2nd dose of rotavirus vaccine between six and 24 weeks of age.</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>No. vaccinated with dose 1</p></td><td><p>No. vaccinated with dose 2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013* <br></p></td><td><p>not available <br></p></td><td><p>not available <br></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>531,068</p></td><td><p>500,454</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015 (up to September)</p></td><td><p>428,591</p></td><td><p>406,485</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source:</em> ImmForm</p><p><em>Note:</em> *Although the immunisation programme was launched in July 2013, January 2014 was the first complete month where all of 25 week old cohort would have been eligible from the programme start.</p><br /><p>In 2014/15 NHS incurred approximately £9 million delivering completed courses of rotavirus vaccination. This figure does not include the cost of the vaccine, which is procured centrally by Public Health England, and is commercially confidential.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-11-11T16:27:06.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425728/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425728/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-03","Rotavirus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of (a) changes in the number of cases of, and deaths from rotavirus (b) the number of rotavirus vaccinations given each year and (c) the cost of delivering that programme of vaccinations on an annual basis since the introduction of the rotavirus vaccine in 2013.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","14562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425729","Department of Health","false","2015-11-11","<p>There have been no such representations or discussions. The prices of branded medicines are controlled by the 2014 Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme or under the statutory scheme established under the Health Service Branded Medicines (Control of Prices and Supply of Information) (No.2) Regulations 2008 and the Health Service Medicines (Information Relating to Sales of Branded Medicines etc.) Regulations 2007.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","14644 ; 14654","2015-11-11T10:03:25.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425729/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425729/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-03","Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent discussions he has had with manufacturers of drugs for cancer treatment on preventing rises in the prices of such drugs.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","14650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425730","Department of Health","false","2015-11-10","<p>Studies estimate that 200,000 - 300,000 people in the United Kingdom are affected by Tourette’s syndrome. Information concerning how many people had Tourette’s syndrome in each of the last five years is not collected.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-11-10T12:31:02.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425730/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425730/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-03","Tourette's Syndrome","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people in each of the last five years had Tourette's syndrome.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","14646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425731","Department of Health","false","2015-11-11","<br /><p>The proportion of people diagnosed between 2006 and 2010 in England (a) as an emergency presentation was 23%, (b) from a general practitioner (GP) referral (including referrals made via the Two Week Wait (TWW) Pathway) was 54% and (c) by a consultant appointment (other outpatient or inpatient elective) was 13%.</p><br /><p>The latest published data is available for 2006 to 2010 from Public Health England’s National Cancer Intelligence Network (NCIN), with an update to these figures taking data up to 2013 being due for publication shortly.</p><br /><p>The breakdown by year is shown in the table below:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>Year</p></td><td colspan="3"><p>Route</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GP - GP referrals and TWW referrals</p></td><td><p>Consultant (other outpatient and inpatient elective)</p></td><td><p>Emergency presentation</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006</p></td><td><p>52%</p></td><td><p>14%</p></td><td><p>24%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007</p></td><td><p>53%</p></td><td><p>13%</p></td><td><p>23%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>54%</p></td><td><p>13%</p></td><td><p>23%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>55%</p></td><td><p>13%</p></td><td><p>22%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>57%</p></td><td><p>12%</p></td><td><p>22%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006-2010</p></td><td><p>54%</p></td><td><p>13%</p></td><td><p>23%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong></strong></p><p><em>Source:</em> <a href="http://www.ncin.org.uk/publications/routes_to_diagnosis" target="_blank">http://www.ncin.org.uk/publications/routes_to_diagnosis</a>.</p><br /><p><em>Notes: </em>A consultant appointment is defined as the proportion diagnosed through the other outpatient and inpatient elective routes.</p><br /><p>The emergency presentation route combines all types of emergency referral – around 6 out of 10 of these are from the A&amp;E department and 3 out of 10 are emergency referrals made by a GP. More information can be found <a href="http://www.ncin.org.uk/view?rid=2174" target="_blank">http://www.ncin.org.uk/view?rid=2174</a> with more detail on the breakdown of the emergency presentation route.</p><br />","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-11-11T16:37:12.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425731/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425731/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-03","Cancer: Diagnosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of people diagnosed with cancer in each of the last five years were diagnosed as a result of attending (a) A&E departments, (b) a GP appointment and (c) a consultant appointment.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","14647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425732","Department of Health","false","2015-11-10","<p>There have been no such discussions.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-11-10T16:25:04.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425732/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425732/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-03","Bone Diseases: Hormones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with clinical bodies on the use of oestrogen to prevent brittle bones.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","14648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425733","Department of Health","false","2015-11-11","<p>The Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA) published a <em>medical device alert, </em>which is<em></em>attached, on 25 September 2015 recommending that all medical devices including breast implants manufactured by Silimed lndustria de lmplantes Ltda. should not be implanted in patients until further advice is issued.</p><br /><p>The agency is actively working with other European regulators on the testing and risk assessment of these products. The assistance of acknowledged national and international clinical and toxicology experts has been enlisted to shape and complete the health risk assessment.</p><br /><p>To ensure thoroughness, testing is being conducted as a 5-stage process. These 5 stages include collection of the required spread of samples; determining the testing methodology; undertaking the testing; analysing the results and evaluating any clinical implications.</p><br /><p>Based on the current available information there is no evidence that this issue poses a threat to patient safety. The MHRA will provide further advice following completion of the European investigation.</p><br /><p>MHRA has set up a <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/devices-made-by-silimed" target="_blank">Silimed implant webpage</a> where patients can register to receive updates and find further information regarding their implants.</p><br /><p>As with all medical devices MHRA continue to monitor their safety and performance and encourage women to report any adverse incidents to its Yellow Card scheme at:</p><br /><p><a href="http://www.yellowcard.mhra.gov.uk" target="_blank">www.yellowcard.mhra.gov.uk</a></p><br /><p>Any women who are concerned should speak to their doctor or surgeon.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-11-11T11:20:35.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425733/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425733/answer","MDA-2015-034 final.docx","MDA-2015-034 final.docx","MHRA medical device alert","MHRA medical device alert","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425733/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-03","Plastic Surgery: Health Hazards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to prevent contamination from breast implants supplied by Silimed of women who have such implants.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","14649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425734","Department of Health","false","2015-11-11","<p>The total number of cases of invasive pneumococcal disease (IPD) and case fatality ratios (CFR) since 2006 are shown in table 1.</p><br /><p>Table 1. Total cases of IPD and case fatality ratios (CFR).</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Total cases<sup>1</sup></p></td><td><p>CFR<sup>2</sup> (%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2004/05</p></td><td><p>6,175</p></td><td><p>not available</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005/06</p></td><td><p>6,250</p></td><td><p>not available</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006/07</p></td><td><p>5,419</p></td><td><p>not available</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007/08</p></td><td><p>5,481</p></td><td><p>not available</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008/09</p></td><td><p>5,569</p></td><td><p>not available</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>5,203</p></td><td><p>13.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>5,265</p></td><td><p>13.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>4,396</p></td><td><p>13.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>4,477</p></td><td><p>13.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>4,032</p></td><td><p>11.9</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><sup>1</sup>Total cases of laboratory confirmed IPD, England and Wales (excluding cases only confirmed by DNA detection and <strong>bronchiolar</strong><strong> <strong>alveolar</strong> <strong>lavage (</strong></strong>BAL) samples).</p><p><sup>2</sup>Proportion of cases of IPD that were found to have died within seven days of IPD onset (excluding BAL) ascertained by tracing GP registration records. Data on CFR prior to 2009 are not available.</p><br /><p>The current PCV offered to infants helps protect against 13 of the 95 known pneumococcal serotypes. The incidence of IPD caused by these serotypes has fallen by 90% in children younger than five years since the introduction in 2005 of PCV in the childhood immunisation programme. The vast majority of IPD cases in this age group are now due to non-vaccine pneumococcal serotypes. In addition, although the vaccine is only given to infants and young children, IPD due to the vaccine serotypes has declined in older children and adults through herd protection. Consequently, there has been a 36% decrease in the number of IPD cases across all age groups between 2005/06 (6,250 IPD cases) and 2013/14 (4,032 IPD cases) in England and Wales (Table 1) because of the infant immunisation programme.</p><br /><p>Pneumococcal conjugate vaccination (PCV) was introduced in September 2006, with a catch-up campaign for children up to two years of age. The number PCV vaccinations given each year are shown in table 2.</p><br /><p>Table 2. The number of children at 12 months of age vaccinated with primary PCV, and the number of children at 24 years of age who have completed the PCV schedule, by year, in England.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial year</p></td><td><p>No. children 12 months vaccinated with primary PCV</p></td><td><p>No. children 24 months vaccinated with completed PCV</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006/07 (Q3&amp;4 only)</p></td><td><p>24,823</p></td><td><p>51,648</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007/08</p></td><td><p>430,518</p></td><td><p>350,049</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008/09</p></td><td><p>570,912</p></td><td><p>487,209</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>599,786</p></td><td><p>561,106</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>618,525</p></td><td><p>582,614</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>641,645</p></td><td><p>615,203</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>651,933</p></td><td><p>636,591</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>640,971</p></td><td><p>642,023</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>617,263</p></td><td><p>633,698</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The complete course comprises three doses of PCV vaccine: these are given at two months and four months (the primary doses), and a booster dose at 12-13 months.</p><br /> <br /><p>In 2014/15 the NHS incurred approximately £9 million delivering completed courses of PCV and <em>Haemophilus influenzae</em> type b / meningococcal C (Hib/MenC) vaccination. Costs in 2013/14 would have been similar. NHS England does not have details of delivery costs prior to 2013/14. This figure does not include the cost of the vaccine, which is procured centrally by PHE, and is commercially confidential.</p><br /><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-11-11T16:45:09.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425734/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425734/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425734/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-03","Pneumococcal Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of (a) changes in the number of cases of, and deaths from pneumococcal disease (b) the number of pneumococcal conjugate vaccine (PCV) vaccinations given each year and (c) the cost of delivering that programme of vaccinations on an annual basis since the introduction of PCV in 2006.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","14561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425735","Cabinet Office","false","2015-11-09","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2015-11-09T11:02:23.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425735/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425735/answer","09112015 PQ 14645.pdf","09112015 PQ 14645.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Lung Cancer","UKSA Letter to Member - Lung Cancer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425735/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-11-03","Lung Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people have been diagnosed with lung cancer in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","14645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425736","Department of Health","false","2015-11-10","<p>Departmental Ministers regularly discuss a range of issues, including diabetes, with their international counterparts. However, there have been no specific discussions on a Global Diabetes Strategy.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-11-10T16:11:37.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425736/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425736/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-03","Diabetes: International Cooperation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with his international counterparts on developing a global strategy to tackle diabetes.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","14643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425737","Department of Health","false","2015-11-11","<p>There have been no such representations or discussions. The prices of branded medicines are controlled by the 2014 Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme or under the statutory scheme established under the Health Service Branded Medicines (Control of Prices and Supply of Information) (No.2) Regulations 2008 and the Health Service Medicines (Information Relating to Sales of Branded Medicines etc.) Regulations 2007.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","14650 ; 14654","2015-11-11T10:03:25.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425737/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425737/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425737/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-03","Insulin","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what representations he has made to manufacturers on minimising increases in the price of insulin for treating type 1 diabetes.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","14644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425738","Department of Health","false","2015-11-10","<p>Our proposals include stronger limits on the hours worked by junior doctors, including to reduce the number of excessive hours junior doctors work each week; and strong contractual safeguards, with external scrutiny, to ensure that employers must address any variations from planned work schedules, to ensure safe working.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-11-10T16:30:26.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425738/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425738/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-03","Junior Doctors: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what his assessment is of the effect of his contractual proposals for junior doctors on the number of hours worked by such doctors in Liverpool.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","14481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425739","Department of Health","false","2015-11-06","<p>Information is available for 2014/15 and is set out in the following table:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p><br></p></td><td><p>Estimated Average Cost per Full-Time Equivalent</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Qualified nurses, midwives and health visitors</p></td><td><p>£42,100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Midwives</p></td><td><p>£45,900</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>All hospital and community health services doctors</p></td><td><p>£96,200</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong></strong></p><p><em>Notes:</em></p><p>Separate figures for qualified nurses are not available. Costs include employer national insurance and pension contributions but not other costs such as recruitment and training (which is not collected centrally).</p><br /><p><em>Source: </em>Department of Health’s Headline HCHS Pay bill Metrics, which are based primarily on earnings statistics published by the Health and Social Care Information Centre, supplemented by employer pension and national insurance contributions estimates informed by unpublished and unvalidated data from the Electronic Staff Record Data Warehouse.</p><br /><p>Future costs will depend on the outcome of the Spending Review and pay recommendations of the independent Pay Review Bodies.</p><br />","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-11-06T14:41:16.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425739/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425739/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-03","Health Professions: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent estimate he has made of the average cost to the NHS of employing a (a) nurse, (b) midwife and (c) doctor; and what forecast he has made of that cost in each year from 2016-17 to 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","14478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425740","Department of Health","false","2015-11-06","<p>The attachment ‘Improving Access to Psychological Therapies Cognitive Behavioural Therapy appointments by CCG’ contains the latest data available on Cognitive Behavioural Therapy (CBT) appointments in clinical commissioning groups (CCGs).</p><br /><p>We do not collect the information as requested for Merseyside. The attachment ‘Improving Access to Psychological Therapies Average – mean - waiting time Cognitive Behavioural Therapy’ contains the latest data available on the average waiting time for a CBT appointment in all CCGs, NHS Halton CCG and other CCGs in the Merseyside area.</p><br />","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","14521","2015-11-06T14:23:36.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425740/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425740/answer","IAPT CBT appointments by CCG.xlsx ; IAPT average mean waiting time CBT.xlsx","IAPT CBT appointments by CCG.xlsx ; IAPT average mean waiting time CBT.xlsx","IAPT CBT appointments by CCG ; IAPT average mean waiting time CBT","IAPT CBT appointments by CCG ; IAPT average mean waiting time CBT","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425740/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-03","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many publicly-funded cognitive behavioural therapy appointments took place in each clinical commissioning group area in England in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","14514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425741","Department of Health","false","2015-11-06","<p>The attachment ‘Improving Access to Psychological Therapies Cognitive Behavioural Therapy appointments by CCG’ contains the latest data available on Cognitive Behavioural Therapy (CBT) appointments in clinical commissioning groups (CCGs).</p><br /><p>We do not collect the information as requested for Merseyside. The attachment ‘Improving Access to Psychological Therapies Average – mean - waiting time Cognitive Behavioural Therapy’ contains the latest data available on the average waiting time for a CBT appointment in all CCGs, NHS Halton CCG and other CCGs in the Merseyside area.</p><br />","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","14514","2015-11-06T14:23:36.79Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425741/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425741/answer","IAPT CBT appointments by CCG.xlsx ; IAPT average mean waiting time CBT.xlsx","IAPT CBT appointments by CCG.xlsx ; IAPT average mean waiting time CBT.xlsx","IAPT CBT appointments by CCG ; IAPT average mean waiting time CBT","IAPT CBT appointments by CCG ; IAPT average mean waiting time CBT","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425741/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-03","Mental Health Services: Waiting Lists","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average waiting time for a cognitive behavioural therapy appointment was in (a) Halton, (b) Merseyside and (c) England in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","14521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425742","Department of Health","false","2015-11-11","<p>The Government remains committed to the Cancer Drugs Fund and is working with NHS England and the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence on the future arrangements for the Fund.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-11-11T16:39:52.61Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425742/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425742/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-03","Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of how many people prescribed drugs funded from the Cancer Drugs Fund are likely to be affected by the planned ending of funding for that fund in March 2016; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","14504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425743","Department of Health","false","2015-11-10","<p>NHS England has published clinical commissioning group (CCG) level expenditure on mental health for 2013/14, which was estimated to be £8.1 billion. CCGs are currently in the process of preparing estimates of expenditure for mental health services in 2014/15.</p><br /><p>We continue to take mental health as seriously as physical health and to hold the National Health Service to account for achieving the objectives set out in the NHS Mandate. In the planning requirements for 2015/16, CCGs were required to invest additionally in mental health in line with their increase in allocation. The total planned additional spend is £376 million, an increase of 4.5%.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-11-10T16:05:54.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425743/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425743/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-03","Mental Health Services: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when his Department plans to release estimates of NHS expenditure on mental health services for financial year 2013-14; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","14551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425744","Department of Health","false","2015-11-06","<p>The table below shows the current expenditure on healthcare for people aged over 65 since 2009/10. This covers total spend on secondary healthcare, primary medical services and prescribing services. Data for 2013/14 and 2014/15 is not available in the format requested.</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p><br></p></td><td><p>Gross Current Expenditure on health care for people aged 65 and over (£000s)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>78,414,543</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>82,091,832</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>84,768,874</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>85,821,639</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>Expenditure on social care for people aged over 65 since 2009/10 from local government funding sources is available on the Health and Social Care Information Centre(HSCIC) (in full) website at the following link. In addition, the National Health Service transferred almost £3.5 billion to local authorities for expenditure on social care, including a transfer worth £1.1 billion in 2014/15. Data is not collected to show how much of this spend is for the elderly compared to working age adults with social care needs.</p><p><a href="http://www.hscic.gov.uk/searchcatalogue?topics=2/Social+care/Social+care+expenditure/Personal+Social+Services+expenditure&amp;sort=Most+recent&amp;size=10&amp;page=1#top" target="_blank">http://www.hscic.gov.uk/searchcatalogue?topics=2/Social+care/Social+care+expenditure/Personal+Social+Services+expenditure&amp;sort=Most+recent&amp;size=10&amp;page=1#top</a></p><p>For 2014/15 HSCIC published provisional data for social care expenditure on 16 September 2015. This can be found at the following link. This is not comparable to previous years because of a change in reporting requirements.</p><p><a href="http://www.hscic.gov.uk/pubs/pssexpcosts1415" target="_blank">http://www.hscic.gov.uk/pubs/pssexpcosts1415</a></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-11-06T14:42:14.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425744/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425744/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-03","Health Services: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much his Department has spent on health and social care for people aged over 65 in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","14583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425745","Department of Health","false","2015-11-06","<br /><p>This information is not held centrally.</p><br /><p>Data gathered by NHS Employers for the purposes of developing proposals on junior doctors’ contract reform (and published in evidence to the Review Body on Doctors and Dentists Remuneration) suggested that junior doctors are rostered to work an average of 63% fewer total hours on a weekend day compared to a week day.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-11-06T14:16:02.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425745/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425745/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-03","Junior Doctors: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number and proportion of junior doctors currently not working weekends.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","14584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425746","Home Office","false","2015-11-10","<p>The attached table contains separate tables for Scotland and Wales which show the number of procedures completed on each species in 2014 by (a) purpose and (b) severity.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","14611","2015-11-10T18:08:14.497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425746/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425746/answer","Table for PQ 14610.xls","Table for PQ 14610.xls","Procedures completed on species","Procedures completed on species","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425746/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425746/answer/previousversion/28183","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-03","Animal Experiments: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Annual Statistics of Scientific Procedures on Living Animals, Great Britain 2014, HC 511, published on 22 October 2015, how many animals of each of the species in that paper were subjected to procedures in establishments in Scotland; and what the (a) purpose and (b) level of security was of those procedures.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","14610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425747","Home Office","false","2015-11-10","<p>The attached table contains separate tables for Scotland and Wales which show the number of procedures completed on each species in 2014 by (a) purpose and (b) severity.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","14610","2015-11-10T18:08:14.573Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425747/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425747/answer","Table for PQ 14610.xls","Table for PQ 14610.xls","Procedures completed on species","Procedures completed on species","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425747/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425747/answer/previousversion/28185","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-03","Animal Experiments: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Annual Statistics of Scientific Procedures on Living Animals, Great Britain 2014, HC 511, published on 22 October 2015, how many animals of each of the species in that paper were subjected to procedures in establishments in Wales; and what the (a) purpose and (b) level of security was of those procedures.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","14611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425748","Home Office","false","2015-11-16","<p>Operational information, which is not publically discloseable, received from the Gangmasters’ Licensing Authority indicates that, since the Authority began operations in 2006, it has seen an increase in the number of vulnerable people being exploited by organised criminals and criminal networks for profit in the sectors it regulates.</p><p>Further information about the role of organised criminal activity would come from the proposed new role of the Director of Labour Market Enforcement who will have a role to gather information on worker exploitation and publish a strategic approach to tackling it.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-11-16T16:47:06.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425748/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425748/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425748/answer/previousversion/28172","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-03","Employment: Organised Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to page 8 of the consultation document Tackling Exploitation in the Labour Market, published in October 2015, if she will publish research conducted by her Department that shows that there has been a shift from abuses of employment regulation towards increasingly organised criminal activity engaged in labour market exploitation over the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","14607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425749","Home Office","false","2015-11-10","<p>Police authorities were abolished in 2012. Police and Crime Commissioners are now responsible for local priorities. The Home Office has estimated the costs of police officers and police community support officers based on average full time equivalent costs and predicted cost increases. The costs include the employers’ portion of National Insurance and pension contributions.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>£</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>2018/19</p></td><td><p>2019/20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Average Officer</p></td><td><p>47,800</p></td><td><p>50,000</p></td><td><p>50,800</p></td><td><p>51,500</p></td><td><p>52,400</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Average PSCO</p></td><td><p>32,300</p></td><td><p>33,400</p></td><td><p>33,800</p></td><td><p>34,200</p></td><td><p>34,700</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-11-10T17:43:11.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425749/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425749/answer","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425749/answer/previousversion/28189","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-03","Police: Per Capita Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent estimate she has made of the average cost to a police authority of employing a (a) police officer and (b) police community support officer; and what estimate she has made of that cost in each year from 2016-17 to 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","14522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425750","Home Office","false","2015-11-11","<p>The information requested could only be provided at disproportionate cost. The available statistics on the timeliness of FOI requests received by the Home Office up to the second quarter of 2015 are published on the Ministry of Justice website at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/government-foi-statistics.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-11-11T16:43:11.383Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425750/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425750/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425750/answer/previousversion/28178","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-03","Home Office: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what average time her Department took to respond to freedom of information requests in each year since 2005.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","14474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425751","Home Office","false","2015-11-10","<p>Information on how many individuals submitted a passport with a counterfeit stamp purporting to a grant settlement, in support of a naturalisation application is not aggregated in national reporting systems. This information could only be obtained by a disproportionately expensive manual case by case search to collate the data.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-11-10T17:52:23.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425751/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425751/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425751/answer/previousversion/28173","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-03","Naturalisation: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many passports submitted in support of an application for naturalisation as a British citizen were found to have a counterfeit Home Office stamp purporting to grant settlement in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","14486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425752","Home Office","false","2015-11-12","<p>Extremist and terrorist organisations such as ISIL are using the internet to disseminate propaganda and recruit individuals to their groups or to support their aims. Despite the vast majority of British Muslims wanting nothing to do with ISIL, some vulnerable individuals, including young people, are being misled by ISIL’s damaging propaganda through its use of social media sites.</p><p>We are therefore working with responsible social media companies to take robust action against terrorist material. Since 2010, over 110,000 pieces of terrorist-related material have been removed at the request of the dedicated Counter-Terrorism Internet Referral Unit (CTIRU). We are pressing social media companies to take stronger, faster and further action to combat the use of their services by terrorist and extremist groups. We want to see a zero tolerance approach to terrorist activity on their networks. We are also working in partnership with civil society organisations prepared to confront the extremist narratives online, increasing their confidence and capability to challenge extremist content effectively and to provide credible alternatives.</p><p>We have seen an increase in the pace and scale of terrorist communications by groups such as ISIL, encouraging vulnerable young people to travel to conflict zones like Syria and Iraq. Therefore, it is essential that we equip young people with an awareness of the dangers of terrorist and extremist propaganda and the skills they need to protect themselves from it. The Home Office funds local projects that encourage young people to think critically about potentially harmful or extremist views presented on the internet through addressing all forms of radicalisation.</p><p>The Prevent statutory duty introduced this year places an obligation on specified authorities to have due regard to preventing people from being drawn into terrorism. This includes, where relevant, having policies in place relating to the use of IT equipment and considering whether IT equipment should use filtering solutions that limit access to terrorist and extremist material. The Channel programme, which is part of the Prevent duty, is a multi-agency process designed to stop people being drawn into terrorism or terrorist related activity. People identified as being at risk of radicalisation from any source, including online radicalisation, are offered tailored support to address their vulnerability. This support often involves specialist intervention providers who understand the ideology of terrorism and extremism and will seek to steer the vulnerable people away from it.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2015-11-12T17:12:06.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425752/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425752/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-03","Radicalism: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government is taking to prevent jihadists recruiting young people through social media sites.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","14632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425753","Home Office","false","2015-11-06","<p>‘Drug Seizures in England and Wales, 2014/15’ was published on 5 November 2015. This statistical release covers the number of drug seizures made by both police forces and Border Force in England and Wales from 2006/07 to 2014/15. The publication can be found at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/seizures-of-drugs-in-england-and-wales-financial-year-ending-2015</p><p>Data specifically on the number of seizures made by police forces and Border Force in England and Wales in 2014/15 can be found in Summary Table 1 of the data tables.</p><p>The Home Office does not hold information centrally on the number of drug seizures in Scotland or Northern Ireland.</p><p>Border Force publishes the number of seizures of drugs at the UK border on Gov.UK: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/border-force-transparency-data-august-2015</p><p>The Home Office and Border Force do no hold any information on the value of drugs seized.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-11-06T13:35:16.68Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425753/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425753/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-03","Drug Seizures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many seizures of illegal drugs took place in the UK in each of the last five years; and what the value was of the drugs seized in each such case.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","14641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425754","Home Office","false","2015-11-10","<p>A full breakdown of all refusals since May 2015, for each Standard Occupational Classification code has been produced as a separate document. I will place a copy of this document in the Library of the House of Commons.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-11-10T17:55:29.63Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425754/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425754/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/425754/answer/previousversion/28194","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-03","Visas: Sponsorship","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 21 September 2015 to Question 9220, if she will place in the Library a full breakdown of all refusals since May 2015 for each Standard Occupational Classification code.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","14626"
